TY  - JOUR
AU  - Gupta, Arpit
AU  - Hansman, Christopher
T1  - Selection, Leverage, and Default in the Mortgage Market
PY  - 2022
Y1  - 2022/02/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhab052
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 35
IS  - 2
SP  - 720
EP  - 770
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We ask whether the correlation between mortgage leverage and default is due to moral hazard (the causal effect of leverage) or adverse selection (ex ante risky borrowers choosing larger loans). We separate these information asymmetries using a natural experiment resulting from the contract structure of option adjustable-rate mortgages and unexpected 2008 divergence of indexes that determine rate adjustments. Our point estimates suggest that moral hazard is responsible for 40$\%$ of the correlation in our sample, while adverse selection explains 60$\%$. We calibrate a simple model to show that leverage regulation must weigh default prevention against distortions due to adverse selection.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhab052
ER  - 



